Note:
WebAssembly Instruction Encoder - Binary Opcode and LEB128 Encoding

This file encodes WebAssembly instructions into their binary representations
for the .wasm binary format. Wasm uses single-byte opcodes with optional
LEB128-encoded operands. Instructions manipulate the Wasm operand stack.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Encode LEB128 unsigned and signed integers for Wasm binary format
- Encode all Wasm MVP opcodes for control flow, stack, locals, memory, and ALU
- Emit complete instruction sequences to output buffers
- Support both 32-bit and 64-bit integer and float operations

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- LEB128 encoding is required for all multi-byte operands in Wasm binary format
- Correct opcode encoding is critical for Wasm module validation
- The Wasm instruction set is stack-based and differs fundamentally from register ISAs
- Proper encoding enables Runa compilation to Wasm for web and WASI targets

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- LEB128 unsigned and signed integer encoding
- Control flow opcodes (block, loop, if, else, end, br, br_if, br_table)
- Local variable opcodes (local.get, local.set, local.tee)
- Memory opcodes (i32.load, i32.store, memory.size, memory.grow)
- Arithmetic opcodes (i32.add, i32.sub, i32.mul, i32.div_s, etc.)
- Comparison opcodes (i32.eqz, i32.eq, i32.ne, i32.lt_s, etc.)
- Constant opcodes (i32.const, i64.const, f32.const, f64.const)
- Call opcodes (call, call_indirect)

Dependencies:
- Imports MachineCode for byte emission to output buffer
- Imports Layout for memory allocation
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WASM BINARY OPCODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
WebAssembly MVP opcodes are single-byte values. Instructions are organized
into functional groups. Each instruction consumes and produces a specific
number of values on the operand stack, forming the basis of Wasm's type
safety through stack typing.
@End Reasoning

